      "writtenOn": "2026-04-15T21:48:06Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This can be massively simplified, avoiding duplicate work, by passing directly the list of files that we know have been already approved by the change owner through a copy label condition and filtering out the ones that have an explicit approval by another owner. \n\n```suggestion\n  private Set\u003cString\u003e getAutoApprovedFiles(\n      Set\u003cString\u003e filesApprovedByChangeOwner,\n      Map\u003cString, Set\u003cGroupOwner\u003e\u003e fileExpandedOwners,\n      Map\u003cAccount.Id, List\u003cPatchSetApproval\u003e\u003e currentApprovalsByAccount) {\n    return filesApprovedByChangeOwner.stream()\n            .filter(notExplicitlyApprovedByAnOwner(fileExpandedOwners, currentApprovalsByAccount))\n            .collect(Collectors.toSet());\n  }\n\n  private Predicate\u003cString\u003e notExplicitlyApprovedByAnOwner(Map\u003cString, Set\u003cGroupOwner\u003e\u003e fileExpandedOwners, Map\u003cAccount.Id, List\u003cPatchSetApproval\u003e\u003e currentApprovalsByAccount) {\n    return filePath -\u003e ownerIds(fileExpandedOwners.get(filePath))\n            .map(currentApprovalsByAccount::get)\n            .filter(Objects::nonNull)\n            .flatMap(List::stream)\n            .noneMatch(isNotCopiedApproval());\n  }\n```",
